Clustering

  1. Home
  2. Clustering

Overview

Clustering is a type of unsupervised learning algorithm used in machine learning and data mining that groups together data points that are similar to each other. The goal of clustering is to identify groups, or clusters, of data points that are similar to each other and different from data points in other groups. The process of clustering involves finding the similarity between data points and grouping them based on that similarity.

There are many different similarity measures that can be used for clustering data, depending on the type of data being analyzed and the goals of the analysis. Some common similarity measures include Euclidean distance, Manhattan distance, and cosine similarity. Euclidean distance measures the straight-line distance between two points in n-dimensional space, while Manhattan distance measures the distance between two points by summing the absolute differences between their coordinates. Cosine similarity measures the angle between two vectors and is often used for text data, where each document is represented as a vector of word frequencies.

When clustering data, it is important to choose the right similarity measure for the type of data being analyzed and the goals of the analysis. Choosing the right similarity measure can help to ensure that data points are grouped together in a meaningful way and that the resulting clusters are useful for the intended purpose. In general, similarity measures should be chosen based on their ability to capture the important features of the data and to distinguish between different groups of data points.

There are two main types of clustering methods: partition and hierarchical clustering. Partition clustering algorithms, such as k-means and fuzzy c-means, partition the data into a fixed number of clusters based on a similarity measure. The algorithm iteratively moves data points between clusters in order to minimize the total distance between data points and their cluster centroids. Partition clustering is a fast and efficient way to cluster large datasets, but it can be sensitive to the initial placement of cluster centroids and may not be suitable for datasets with complex or non-linear structures.

On the other hand, hierarchical clustering algorithms, such as agglomerative and divisive clustering, create a hierarchical structure of clusters based on the similarity between data points. Agglomerative clustering starts with each data point in its own cluster and iteratively merges the most similar clusters until all data points are in a single cluster. Divisive clustering starts with all data points in a single cluster and iteratively divides the cluster into smaller clusters based on their dissimilarity. Hierarchical clustering can be useful for exploring the structure of complex datasets, but it can be computationally expensive and may not be suitable for large datasets.

In summary, clustering is a powerful technique for analyzing and understanding complex datasets. By identifying groups of similar data points, clustering can help to reveal underlying patterns and relationships in the data. The choice of clustering algorithm and similarity measure will depend on the nature of the data being analyzed and the goals of the analysis.

In this project, we will use two different clustering algorithms, k-means clustering and hierarchical clustering, to analyze the Amazon reviews dataset. The goal of this analysis is to observe how these algorithms can separate different categories of products and different review ratings based on the similarity between the reviews. We will use the k-means algorithm with the Euclidean distance similarity measure and the hierarchical clustering algorithm with the cosine similarity measure to cluster the reviews.

The k-means algorithm is a partition clustering algorithm that is commonly used for clustering large datasets. It partitions the data into a fixed number of clusters based on the similarity measure. In our case, we will use the Euclidean distance as the similarity measure to determine the distance between data points. This algorithm will allow us to cluster reviews based on their similarity, which can help us to identify different categories of products and review ratings. On the other hand, hierarchical clustering is a method that creates a hierarchical structure of clusters based on the similarity between data points. We will use the cosine similarity measure to cluster the reviews in a hierarchical structure, which can help us to identify clusters at different levels of granularity. This approach can reveal the underlying structure of the data and help us to gain insights into the relationships between different products and review ratings in the Amazon reviews dataset.

Part 1 - Numerical Data

Data Preparation

The first step in this process was to use the cleaned and processed data files mentioned above and combine the information.

meta_df_1000 = pd.read_parquet('meta_df_1000_cleaned.parquet')
reviews_df = pd.read_parquet('reviews_df_clean.parquet')

merged_df = pd.merge(meta_df_1000, reviews_df, on='asin', how='inner')
merged_df['category_1'] = merged_df.category.apply(lambda x: x[1])
merged_df['rating'] = merged_df['rating'].astype(float)
merged_df.info()

This shows all the columns in our combined dataset from the metadata and user reviews.

We can observe in the above data that we have a lot of object columns and a very few numerical columns. Therefore, some preparation and transformation are needed before we can start the analysis.

We will first create a new dataframe that contains a subset of the columns in merged_df that can be used for clustering. We will call this new dataframe clus_df1.

clus_df1 = merged_df[['brand', 'price', 'found_helpful', 'verified_purchase', 'category_1']].copy()
clus_df1.head()

The output shows the first 5 rows ofclus_df1:

We can already see that the brand column contains some rows with blank values.

On inspection

clus_df1[clus_df1['brand'] == ""]

we see that there are only 7 such rows out of 5921 total entries.

We will drop these rows.

clus_df1 = clus_df1[~clus_df1['brand'].str.fullmatch('')]
clus_df1.sample(10)

We see that the output now does not have the missing brands. But what about prices?

The ouput of the info() call on merged_df showed that prices have 3066 non-null values out of 5921. We also need to handle these missing values. Since we cannot drop all these rows, we will use the mean of proces in each category to fill them.

clus_df1['price'] = clus_df1.groupby(['category_1']).price.transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.mean()))
clus_df1 = clus_df1.dropna(subset='price')
clus_df1.sample(10)

In the ouptput above, all the rows have prices values filled in.

We will also create bins for the found_helpful column in the same way that we did in Data Prep and EDA. We are doing this because this column has a large number of small values and a few very large values. Any form of normalization will, in my opinion, lead to high disparities in values and so having bins that are based on observed frequencies of values in the column can make these values more comparable.

clus_df1['found_helpful_bins'] = pd.cut(clus_df1.found_helpful, [0,1,2,3,4,6,11,651], include_lowest=True, labels=np.arange(7))
clus_df1['verified_purchase'] = clus_df1['verified_purchase'].astype(int)

In the above snippet, verified_purcahse column was also converted to being numeric since it is a boolean variable. We can see a new column in the output that has the corresponding bins for the found_helpful column based on our cuts.

As a last step, the brand and category_1 columns need to be converted to one-hot encoding in order to be included in the clustering.

clus_df1_dummies = pd.get_dummies(clus_df1, columns=['brand', 'category_1'])
clus_df1_dummies.sample(10)

The final processed dataframe looks as shown below.

We can now use this data to perform KMeans clustering.

For starting our analysis we will set the values of k=5 to check if there is any relation between the reating and the clusters that are created.

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.manifold import TSNE
kmeans = KMeans(5).fit(clus_df1_dummies)

The results of the clustering with visualization are described in the Results section.

Results

Before we try to visualize the clusters created lets look at the distribution of clusters.

np.unique(kmeans.labels_, return_counts=True)

merged_df.rating.value_counts()

As is quite apparent from these distributions, it seems that the clusters might not be able to represent the ratings in our user reviews.

However, lets try to plot the clusters and see how good or bad the relation between assogned clusters and rating is.

trans_points = TSNE(n_components=2).fit_transform(clus_df1_dummies)
fig = px.scatter(x=trans_points[:, 0], y=trans_points[:, 1], color=kmeans.labels_, symbol=merged_df.loc[clus_df1.index, 'rating'])
fig.update(layout_coloraxis_showscale=False)
fig.show()

The colours in the plot represent the clusters created by kmeans and the markers types represent the rating in the dataset. On careful observation we see that all clusters contain a mixture of marker types and there is hardly any spearation in ratings created by the clusters. Therefore, we can conclude that the clustering using kmeans using euclidean distance for k=5 does not result in clusters that are related to ratings.

One of the problems in this transformation of the dataset is that there are very few columns and therefore not a lot of information is included in it. Also, the number of brands in the dataset are huge with 20-30 brands that apper frequntly and the rest appearing very scarcely. Therefore, the conversion of the brands column to one-hot encoding create a large number of variables and increase the dimensionality of the data sognificantly while not adding as much information.

In the next part, we will try to use the text columns in out dataset to check if the clusters created using features obtained from text can show any realtionships with ratings or categories of products.

We will use this data to create a vectorized representation of reviews using the CountVectorizer. But before that, we need to preprocess the text to remove punctuation and stopwords.

nlp = spacy.load('en_core_web_sm')
merged_df['tokens'] = merged_df['content'].apply(lambda x: nlp(x.lower())) 
merged_df['tokens'] = merged_df.tokens.apply(lambda x: [w.lemma_ for w in x if not w.is_stop and not w.is_punct and w.lemma_!=' '])
merged_df['tokens'] = merged_df['tokens'].apply(lambda x: ' '.join(x))
merged_df['tokens'].head(10)

This is very similar to what is done in Data Prep and EDA to visualize text data. This snippet first comverts the text to lower case and applies lemmatization on words. It also removes stopwords and punctuation. Finally the tokens are converted back to space separated strings that are expected by CountVectorizer.

Below are a few rows from the output after this process.

We can now use the count vectorizer to transform this text into vectors.

from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
vectorizer = CountVectorizer()
tokens_vectorized = vectorizer.fit_transform(merged_df['tokens'])
tokens_vectorized.shape
(5921, 14169)

We can see that we have 5921 vectors, each with dimensions 14169.

We now have data in the proper format to begin clustering. Again like in the last part, lets start with 5 clusters to check if these can separate reviews with different ratings. Later we can run silhouette analysis and elbow method to check what are the ideal number of clusters based on these methods and try to run clusteing again using those values.

kmeans_1 = KMeans(5).fit(tokens_vectorized)

Results

We have our results stored in kmeans_1. Lets create a 2D representation of out data using TSNE method and plot the clusters in the same way we did in Part 1.

trans_points = TSNE(n_components=2, init="random").fit_transform(tokens_vectorized)

This snippet generates the following plot.

If you zoom into the graph and pan around, you will observe that this is not very different from the results we obtained in Part 1. All clusters contain all shapes of markers, meaning, clusters are not sepearted by the rating in the dataset.

Lets try to improve our clustering results by comparing the silhouette plots for different number of clusters. We will use the yellowbricks package in python to create the silhouette plots.

range_n_clusters = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8, 10]

for n in range_n_clusters:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=n, init='k-means++', n_init=10, 
                    max_iter=300, tol=0.0001, verbose=0, 
                    random_state=None, copy_x=True, algorithm='lloyd')
    visualizer = SilhouetteVisualizer(kmeans, colors='yellowbrick')

    visualizer.fit(tokens_vectorized)        # Fit the data to the visualizer
    print ('silhouette_score_', visualizer.silhouette_score_)
    visualizer.show()        # Finalize and render the figure

This code generates the plots shown below. We have used the values of k as 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8, 10 for creatting these plots.

The plots do not show a good clustering fit for any of the above values. Most of them have one or two very huge clusters with very small number of points in the remaining clusters. Also, some of the plots show large number of points having negative silhouette coefficients indicating very bad clustring results.

Maybe CountVectorizer is not able to represent the data very well to be able to separate it into meaninglful clusters.This may be because of some highly frequent words (observed in visualization in Data Prep and EDA), that are not stopwords, that are being used across all reviews. These words may be adding noise in the dataset and as a result the clusters are being formed at rondom. If this is the case, TFIDF may provide a better representation of the review text for our purpose as it asigns lower values to such highly frequent terms in the corpus. Lets give it a try.

Part 3 - Text Data (TFIDF)

Data Preparation and code

Here we do not have a lot of preparation to do as we already have the cleaned text data. We just need to transform the text data using TFIDF Vectorizer.

from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer()
tokens_vectorized = vectorizer.fit_transform(merged_df['tokens'])
tokens_vectorized.shape
(5921, 14169)

We again have 5921 vectors of 14169 dimensions.

Lets run the silhouette analysis for the TFIDF vectors to see if we get better results. We will run KMeans clustering for each of the values of k (2,3,4,5,6,8,10) and also plot the solhouette scores to visualize how good the clusters are.

range_n_clusters = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8, 10]

for n in range_n_clusters:
    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15, 6))
    
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=n, init='k-means++', n_init=10, 
                    max_iter=300, tol=0.0001, verbose=0, 
                    random_state=None, copy_x=True, algorithm='lloyd')
    visualizer = SilhouetteVisualizer(kmeans, colors='yellowbrick', ax=ax1)

    visualizer.fit(tokens_vectorized)        # Fit the data to the visualizer
    print ('silhouette_score_', visualizer.silhouette_score_)
    pl = sns.scatterplot(x=trans_points[:, 0], y=trans_points[:, 1], hue=np.array(visualizer.estimator.labels_, dtype='str'), style=merged_df.loc[:, 'rating'])
    ax2 = pl.axes
    ax1.title.set_text('Silhouette Plot, score={}'.format(visualizer.silhouette_score_))
    ax2.title.set_text('KMeans Clustering')
    fig.show()        # Finalize and render the figure

Results

The run generates the following plots.

Although the silhouette plots are better than Part 2, they can not be called good. We still have a large cluster, for almost every value of k, that has most points with negative silhouette coefficients. Also, the scatter plots still have a mix of ratings in every cluster with almost no separation.

We will also try to check if the clusters can separate out categories in the dataset. But before that lets plot silhouette scores and number of clusters to check what is the ideal number of cluster according to this method.

kmeans = KMeans()
visualizer = KElbowVisualizer(kmeans, metric='silhouette', k=(2,15))

The plot suggests that 2 is the best value of clusters, although the plot does not have the conventional shape that a silhouette plot generally has. The silhouette value keeps increasing as the number of clusters increase. We have 14 categories in the dataset. Although all values of silhouette score are not very good (very low silhouette scores), since we want to compare the clusters with categories in our dataset, lets use k=16. We are doing this since there is a peak at k-16.

Lets plot the clusters in 2 dimensions first.

We can still see that a clear separation does not exist. We can see that there are mixed markers in all clusters.

Lets try to determine how good this separation is by using a heatmap to see how many points from each category lie in each cluster.

Heirarchical Clustering

In this section we will use another clustering method, the agglomerative heirarchical clustering to perform analysis on the dataset. We will again try to understand what are the type of points that cluster together and are there any inherent relationships between these clusters and characteristics in our dataset. We will try to understand if the points that are clustered together have any pattern or anything in common and if so, we will try to reason why this might be possible.

The distance metric that we will be using for heirarchical clustering is cosine distance. It is defined as follows

$$ {cosine \ distance = 1 - \frac{A.B}{\left|A\right|\left|B\right|}} $$

where code A and B are two vectors whose distance needs to be calculated.

Data Preparation and Code

We already have the vectorized text that was created in the last section. Out of the CountVectorizer and TfidfVectorizer, we will use the vectors created using TfidfVectorizer, since they are better at assigning importance to words. We will run heirarchical clustering in R. So lets first load the vectorized reviews.

reviews <- read_csv('tokens_vectorized.csv')
reviews = reviews[-1]
head(reviews)

In the above snippet, we load the stored vectors from csv format and remove the index column. The first few rows look as shown below.

The column names in the output above indicates the word and the values in a corresponding row indicates the vale of the word in that document as computed by TfidfVectorizer.

As the next step, we will compute the cosine distance matrix for all the rows in out data.

scaled = scale(t(reviews))
scaled[is.na(scaled)] = 0
scaled = as.matrix(scaled)

sim1 <- scaled / sqrt(colSums(scaled * scaled))
sim1[is.na(sim1)] = 0
sim1[is.infinite(sim1)] = 0

sim <- t(sim1) %*% sim1
dim(sim) 
cos_dist = as.dist(1 - sim)

This snippet first scales all the vecors in the dataset. It then divides every vector by its magnitude and converts every vector into a unit vector. Now the dot product of these vectors should directly give us the cosine similarity. Finally we substract the cosine similarity from 1 to get the cosine distance.

The output of dim(sim) line is shown below.

[1] 5921 5921

This makes sense as we have 5921 vectors.

Now that we have out distance matrix, we can use it to run heirarchical clustering on the vectors.

hclust_avg <- hclust(cos_dist, method = 'average')
hclust_ward <- hclust(cos_dist, method = 'ward.D')
hclust_comp <- hclust(cos_dist, method = 'complete')

This clustering results using cosine distance for our dataset using different linkage methods are stored in hclust_avg, hclust_ward and hclust_comp

Results

Lets analyse our results to see what kind of clusters are created using each method.

We will first plot the dendrograms using dendextend for each of the linkage methods.

hclust_avg <- hclust(cos_dist, method = 'average')
hcd <- as.dendrogram(hclust_avg)
cut_avg <- cutree(hclust_avg, k = 10)

avg_col_dend <- color_labels(color_branches(hcd, k = 10), k = 10)
avg_col_dend <- assign_values_to_leaves_nodePar(avg_col_dend, 0.2, "lab.cex")

nodePar <- list(lab.cex = 0.1,
                cex = 0.07)
plot(avg_col_dend, 
      main="Dendogram for hclust using 'average' method for 10 colored clusters", 
      nodePar=nodePar)

Repeating the process for ward.D and complete methods we get the following.

                cex = 0.07)
plot(comp_col_dend, 
      main="Dendogram for hclust using 'complete' method for 10 colored clusters", 
      nodePar=nodePar)

Result:

Looking at the results, we can already see that the clustering for the average method is not so good since it creates 1 very large cluster having almost all the elements. The results for ward.D and complete are better but we cannot compare and analyse the results with respect to our dataset since the number of labels on the x axis are too large to differetiate between. So, lets use some other visualization techniques to makwe this analysis.

We will start with observing how many points are assigned to each cluster is each of the methods.

The plots for cluster vs rating for both the methods show that there is hardly any relation. The situation is same in case of cluster vs category in case of ward.D. Most the points from all categories are assigned to 1 large cluster and the smaller cluster do not have any good separation as well. But the last plot between cluster and category using complete method shows some interesting results. Lets discuss some patterns.

  • We see that the Computer & Accesories category has most points in the cluster 5.
  • Headphones has a large number of points in cluster 8.
  • Although Camera & Photo has a large number of points in cluster 5, it also has a large number of points in cluster 3 and hence there is some observable separation.
  • We observe that Portable Audio & Video has most points in cluster 5 and 8. This is very similar to distribution of Headphones category and this makes sense since headphones are also portable audio devices.
  • Wearable Technology has the most points in cluster 6.

Conclusion

We have made quite a few observations while performing all the analysis above using K-Means clustering and heirarchical clustering. Our goal was to determine of clustering data using similarity measures, can help us find some patterns wothin the dataset and to observe what methods and measures of distance provide what information. In out analysis using using K-Means clustering, we first made use of numerical columns in our dataset. We observed that the numerical columns in the dataset contained very sparce information. The column found_helpful comtained very skewed data and had mostly 0 and 1 in a large percent of the rows. Therefore it did not hold a lot of information required to differetiate points in our dataset. Similarly the brand column contained few popular barnds and a lot of unpopular brands with just a handful of products. As a result, when it was converted to one-hot encoding, the number of dimension blew-up and not a lot of information was added. The euclidean distance between any two rare brands, for example, would just be sqrt(2) and this would not provide usable distances between data points. Other than these, we had verified_purchase column which was a binary field. All these issues made it difficut to find dissimilarities within points in the dataset.

Having made these observations, an attempt was made to use the text content of each review to cluster the data as this might hold a lot of information about how good the product is or what the product is good or bad at. Although, while tranforming the text data to vectors that out algorithms can handle, what information is retained greatly depends on what tranformation we use. In this case, CountVectorizer and TfidfVectorizer were used. We did not observe any interesting patterns in both of these cases. The reason might be that we were using vectors with 14k dimensions and only 6K data points. This made the transform vectors very sparce and as a result, euclidean distance was not able to efficiently distinguish between data points. We may also attribute the observed results to the tranformations we used. CountVectorizer contains the counts of all the words used in the data, and as long as a there is very little overlap in the words used, the euclidean distance measure is not going to provide meaningful distances and there is no common dimension to compare on. These claims are also supported by the observed silhouette plots. We found very bad clusters with huge number of points with negative silhouette coefficients. This conveys that KMeans had created clusters where no clear clusters could actually be created.

We then tried to use heirarchical using cosine similarity. Cosine similarity is expected to work better with hight dimensional sparse data. This time we directly jumped to data transformed using the TfidfVectorizer since our observations during K-Means clustering had confirmed that the numerical data did not contain a lot of information to work with. Here we wanted to observe if the data could be separated into clusters in any meaningful manner. So we computer the distance matrix based on cosine similarity and clustered the data using agglomerative heirarchical clustering. To make analysis we cut the tree at 10 clusters and made analysis to observe patterns in the clusters. We made use of average, ward.D and complete linkage methods for the clustering. We observed that average methods was barely able to distinguish between clusters and created on large cluster with very few points in all other clusters. with ward.D, we did observe some distribution in the number of points in each cluster but there was not notable relationship between these clusters and rating/category columns in the dataset. In case of complete linkage method, we made some interesting observations and the clusters created were able to create some separation with respect to product categories. Although these relationships were not strong, this was the best result we obtained during our analysis in this section.

Throughout this analysis we were able to work with and compare the results on clustering using different distance measures and algorithms. Although the final results were not as eciting, we did gain a deeper understanding of our dataset and the workings of the variuos algorithms and methods used.

In conclusion, our analysis of the Amazon reviews dataset using clustering techniques has provided valuable insights into the relationships between different categories of products and review ratings. By using k-means clustering and hierarchical clustering, we were able to observe how the data can be grouped into distinct clusters, providing a visual representation of the patterns and relationships within the data. These insights can be useful for businesses to better understand their customers and improve their offerings. For example, businesses can use these clustering results to identify which products are popular among different customer segments, and tailor their marketing and product development strategies accordingly.

Overall, the clustering analysis using k-means and hierarchical clustering has demonstrated the usefulness of these techniques in exploring and understanding complex datasets, and can be used in a wide range of applications in various industries.
